own to ",[92,1596,1597],{},"-0.5"," but opacity which in css is ",[92,1600,1601],{},"0-1"," goes from ",[92,1604,1605],{},"0-100"," ???",[56,1608,1609,1610,1613,1614,1519,1617,1620,1621,1624],{},"I can understand not always using the same scales (e.g. ",[92,1611,1612],{},"sm"," , ",[92,1615,1616],{},"md",[92,1618,1619],{},"xl"," vs ",[92,1622,1623],{},"0-*",") but for some of the odder names, because the auto complete does not work based on the css property name, it can be very hard to find the utility you want. I have to keep the docs opened and pinned for actual searching. But I guess that could be considered more the autocomplete's fault, and not tailwind.",[1580,1626,1628],{"id":1627},"missing-utilities","Missing Utilities",[56,1630,1631,1632,153],{},"Some css properties that are now pretty usable, do not exist yet. For example, text-shadow does not exist because ",[69,1633,1636],{"href":1634,"rel":1635},"https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss/issues/162#issuecomment-777889883",[73],"which default styles to add has not been decided yet",[56,1638,1639],{},"Which fair, but I really wish they would at least they were provided as experimental properties or something instead of having to rely on other's plugins.",[56,1641,1642,1643,1646,1647,153],{},"Also some which should really exist, don't, such as grid with ",[92,1644,1645],{},"auto-fill"," and ",[92,1648,1649],{},"auto-fit",[1580,1651,1653],{"id":1652},"hard-to-use-existing-tailwind-variables-in-custom-utilities","Hard to use Existing Tailwind Variables in Custom Utilities",[56,1655,1656,1657,1660],{},"I've written a few custom utilities for gradients, but couldn't for example, re-use the to/from-* gradient utilities and the css variables they create\nbecause I can't seperate the part I need (the color). For example, ",[92,1658,1659],{},"from-black from-0%"," will create:",[138,1662,1664],{"className":963,"code":1663,"language":123,"meta":133,"style":133},"-tw-gradient-from-position: 0%;\n--tw-gradient-from: #000 var(--tw-gradient-from-position);\n\n// which are then used like this:\n--tw-gradient-stops: var(--tw-gradient-from);\n",[92,1665,1666,1671,1682,1688,1693],{"__ignoreMap":133},[146,1667,1668],{"class":148,"line":149},[146,1669,1670],{"class":184},"-tw-gradient-from-position: 0%;\n",[146,1672,1673,1676,1679],{"class":148,"line":163},[146,1674,1675],{"class":184},"--tw-gradient-from: ",[146,1677,1678],{"class":152},"#",[146,1680,1681],{"class":184},"000 var(--tw-gradient-from-position);\n",[146,1683,1684],{"class":148,"line":191},[146,1685,1687],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":1686},true,"\n",[146,1689,1690],{"class":148,"line":212},[146,1691,1692],{"class":184},"// which are then used like this:\n",[146,1694,1695],{"class":148,"line":225},[146,1696,1697],{"class":184},"--tw-gradient-stops: var(--tw-gradient-from);\n",[56,1699,1700,1701,1704],{},"I can use the position, but not the color, there is no ",[92,1702,1703],{},"--tw-gradient-from-color",", so I have to create my own which can get messy.",[1580,1706,1708],{"id":1707},"dynamic-values","Dynamic values",[56,1710,1711],{},"The stylesheet is compiled at build time (so that unused styles can be removed), so this means you can't use dynamic styles. This will not work. You have to use an inline style tag or a script tag.",[138,1713,1717],{"className":1714,"code":1715,"language":1716,"meta":133,"style":133},"language-vue shiki shiki-themes material-theme-lighter material-theme material-theme-palenight","\u003Cdiv :class=\"`p-[${customValue}]`\">\n\u003C/div>\n\n","vue",[92,1718,1719,1752],{"__ignoreMap":133},[146,1720,1721,1723,1725,1727,1729,1731,1734,1737,1740,1743,1745,1748,1750],{"class":148,"line":149},[146,1722,488],{"class":152},[146,1724,525],{"class":491},[146,1726,791],{"class":152},[146,1728,500],{"class":263},[146,1730,503],{"class":152},[146,1732,1733],{"class":152},"\"`",[146,1735,1736],{"class":535},"p-[",[146,1738,1739],{"class":152},"${",[146,1741,1742],{"class":184},"customValue",[146,1744,631],{"class":152},[146,1746,1747],{"class":535},"]",[146,1749,810],{"class":152},[146,1751,517],{"class":152},[146,1753,1754,1756,1758],{"class":148,"line":163},[146,1755,546],{"class":152},[146,1757,525],{"class":491},[146,1759,517],{"class":152},[951,1761,1763],{"id":1762},"conclusion","Conclusion",[56,1765,1766],{},"I've been using it now for a few months and I can never go back to the old way.",[1768,1769,1772,1777],"section",{"className":1770,"dataFootnotes":133},[1771],"footnotes",[951,1773,1776],{"className":1774,"id":132},[1775],"sr-only","Footnotes",[1778,1779,1780,1791],"ol",{},[85,1781,1783,1784],{"id":1782},"user-content-fn-1","I know, I could apply all the classes to the wrapper as well or use some BEM naming scheme and simplify the css, but then in complex elements, they need to be attached/created for every element which might only use a single state class, which probably isn't an issue performance wise if the classes aren't changing every second, but just irks me. And conditionally giving them the needed classes is beyond painful so I often stuck with this. ",[69,1785,1790],{"href":1786,"ariaLabel":1787,"className":1788,"dataFootnoteBackref":133},"#user-content-fnref-1","Back to reference 1",[1789],"data-footnote-backref","â†©",[85,1792,1794,1795],{"id":1793},"user-content-fn-2","I had trouble getting it to work with vscode + vue. Also you must type the name exactly and this is hard given the inconsistent naming. ",[69,1796,1790],{"href":1797,"ariaLabel":1798,"className":1799,"dataFootnoteBackref":133},"#user-content-fnref-2","Back to reference 2",[1789],[1801,1802,1803],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMK4o, html code.shiki .sMK4o{--shiki-light:#39ADB5;--shiki-default:#89DDFF;--shiki-dark:#89DDFF}html pre.shiki code .swJcz, html code.shiki .swJcz{--shiki-light:#E53935;--shiki-default:#F07178;--shiki-dark:#F07178}html pre.shiki code .spNyl, html code.shiki .spNyl{--shiki-light:#9C3EDA;--shiki-default:#C792EA;--shiki-dark:#C792EA}html pre.shiki code .sTEyZ, ht